      "arguments": {
        "file_path": "/logs/agent/solution.md",
        "old_string": "### Implementation\n\nThe core issue is at **line 835 in Sender.java**, within the `failBatch()` method:\n\n```java\nmaybeRemoveAndDeallocateBatch(batch);  // UNSAFE for in-flight batches\n```\n\nThis unconditionally deallocates the buffer, but the batch's request might still be queued in the NetworkClient's `inFlightRequests` (line 616 in NetworkClient.doSend()).\n\n**Solution: Don't deallocate buffers in failBatch() - let completeBatch() handle it**\n\nThe fix requires modifying `failBatch()` to avoid deallocating buffers for batches that are still in-flight. Instead of:\n\n```diff\n- maybeRemoveAndDeallocateBatch(batch);\n```\n\nWe should:\n\n```diff\n+ // Don't deallocate buffer here - it's still in-flight in NetworkClient.\n+ // The buffer will be deallocated in completeBatch() when response arrives.\n+ // If response never arrives, the connection closure will clean it up.\n+ maybeRemoveFromInflightBatches(batch);\n```\n\nThis change ensures that:\n1. **The batch is removed from tracking** via `maybeRemoveFromInflightBatches()` (line 173)\n2. **The buffer remains allocated** while in-flight\n3. **Safe deallocation happens in completeBatch()** (line 750) when the response is received\n4. **No corruption occurs** because the Send object always has valid buffer contents\n\n**Key insight**: The buffer deallocation should happen at the END of the batch lifecycle (when response is received), not when the batch expires. The expiration just marks it as failed, but the network layer must finish using it first.",
        "new_string": "### Implementation\n\nThe fix requires TWO changes to Sender.java to prevent deallocating buffers while they're still in-flight:\n\n**Change 1: failBatch() - Don't deallocate immediately (line 817-836)**\n\nThe core issue is at **line 835 in Sender.java**:\n\n```java\nmaybeRemoveAndDeallocateBatch(batch);  // UNSAFE - buffer still in-flight!\n```\n\nThis should be changed to:\n\n```diff\n- maybeRemoveAndDeallocateBatch(batch);\n+ // Don't deallocate buffer here - the request is still queued in NetworkClient.\n+ // The buffer reference is held by the Send object in inFlightRequests.\n+ // We'll deallocate when the response arrives (in completeBatch) or connection closes.\n+ maybeRemoveFromInflightBatches(batch);\n```\n\n**Change 2: completeBatch() - Deallocate even if batch already failed (line 744-752)**\n\nThe response handler must deallocate buffers for batches that were already marked failed:\n\n```diff\nprivate void completeBatch(ProducerBatch batch, ProduceResponse.PartitionResponse response) {\n    if (transactionManager != null) {\n        transactionManager.handleCompletedBatch(batch, response);\n    }\n\n    if (batch.complete(response.baseOffset, response.logAppendTime)) {\n        maybeRemoveAndDeallocateBatch(batch);\n-   }\n+   } else if (batch.isDone()) {\n+       // Batch already completed (failed by failBatch due to expiration)\n+       // Still need to deallocate the buffer now that request is no longer in-flight\n+       maybeRemoveAndDeallocateBatch(batch);\n+   }\n}\n```\n\nTogether, these changes ensure:\n1. **Expired batches are marked failed immediately** (user gets error notification via `completeExceptionally()`)\n2. **Buffers remain valid until network write completes** (Send object can safely serialize the batch)\n3. **Safe deallocation happens after request is done** (when response arrives or connection closes)\n4. **No corruption occurs** because the batch's buffer is never reused while in-flight",
